LANDFIRE and Certified Sustainable Forest Management

2 LANDFIRE for forest assessment


In the following tutorial, we explore the use of LANDFIRE data products in assessing forest ecosystem characteristics relevant to forest certification criteria.

Assessing forest condition to inform active forest management may include:


  • Comparing changes in composition and spatial patterns of historical and current communities
  • Assessing successional states of those ecosystems, past and present
  • Understanding natural disturbance regimes


These steps, while foundational and conceptually simple, can be difficult due to the lack of data, especially when pursuing them at a landscape scale. LANDFIRE data products and ecological models offer cover of the conterminous United States, and are appropriate for large scale assessments when information is difficult or not attainable from ground surveys.

In the following technical guide, we explore the Ataya tract of the Cumberland Forest Plateau, a TNC-managed forest in Central Appalachia (outlined in the map below).


Tutorial Goals

  • Develop an understanding of some of the available LANDFIRE data products
  • Provide a roadmap of the technical steps and tools to replicate such an assessment on a novel area of interest
  • Perform GIS assessment and produce visuals (e.g., maps and charts) to support findings
  • Practice making inferences from assessment results, including troubleshooting unexpected results


Forest Certification

The Ataya forest tract, hereafter “Ataya,” is managed in accordance with standards set forth by a third-party forest auditor. Third-party certification entities evaluate forest management to defined standards that ensure sustainable management practices and provide confidence to consumers of forest products. Certification standards often include goals or requirements to manage and restore native ecosystems.

For this tutorial, we focus on two ecological criteria: environmental value, and management of high conservation value areas. Forest managers can apply the following analysis to leverage high-quality, open-source data (LANDFIRE data products) to drive sustainable forestry on suitable sites.


LANDFIRE

LANDFIRE is an interagency program within the United States that “provides 20+ national geo-spatial layers (e.g. vegetation, fuel, disturbance, etc.), databases, and ecological models that are available to the public for the US and insular areas.” With this free and regularly updated data, it is possible to conduct analysis supporting a multitude of ecological inquiries.
